  "narrative": "Case live_in_aide_case_001 was evaluated using privacy mode `inferred_from_living_room_sleeping`. The current rule set concludes that the housing arrangement results in a violation. The strongest theory triggered is constructive denial of accommodation. Sleep interruption was established from living-room sleeping plus night access needs. Privacy loss was treated as a relevant harm in the necessity analysis.",
  "explanations": {
    "necessary": "Necessity was triggered because the accepted facts established one or more functional harms. Supporting authorities: McGary v. City of Portland, HUD/DOJ Joint Statement on Reasonable Accommodations",
    "reasonable": "Reasonableness was satisfied because medical support and necessity were present and no defenses defeated the request. Supporting authorities: Giebeler v. M&B Associates, United States v. California Mobile Home Park Management Co., HUD/DOJ Joint Statement on Reasonable Accommodations, 24 CFR 982.316",
    "dutyToGrant": "The evaluator found a duty to grant because disability, live-in aide need, request, and reasonableness were all present. Supporting authorities: Giebeler v. M&B Associates, United States v. California Mobile Home Park Management Co., McGary v. City of Portland, 24 CFR 982.316",
    "constructiveDenial": "Constructive denial was triggered because approval in principle was followed by denial of an effective functional arrangement. Supporting authorities: United States v. California Mobile Home Park Management Co., McGary v. City of Portland",
    "violation": "Violation was triggered by either denied duty-to-grant logic or constructive denial logic. Supporting authorities: Giebeler v. M&B Associates, United States v. California Mobile Home Park Management Co., McGary v. City of Portland, 24 CFR 982.316"
